Hi,

I don&#39;t agree with this. Imagine that you have class with one point of entry 
for the client i.e. one public method. You can&#39;t change the access modifier 
of your method just to test it. Wrapping your private method in a public 
method is just the same as changing the access modifier. It is will 
documented and it works to use java reflection.

The developers in the project I am currently working changed their private 
methods to public just to UNIT test their code. It is currently very 
important to test the private methods as it accounts for over 60% of the 
functionality and logic. I have found that enables me to test bottom up and 
I have more confidence when coding and when I need to refactor.

I have posted the SecureClassAccess.java in the &quot;files&quot; section of group for 
anyone that does want to us it to test their private methods.

A+ David

On 30/08/05, Richa Kishore &lt;brajkiricha@...&gt; wrote: 
&gt; 
&gt;  You can&#39;t test a private method directly in JUnit.
&gt; 
&gt; A method is private, it means the business of the
&gt; method is specific to the class only.
&gt; 
&gt; SO, if you want to test a private method write a
&gt; poublic method, which is calling the private method
&gt; and then write a junit test for this new public
&gt; method.
